  <title translate="true">Multitopics_PDFNamedLinkHTML</title>
  <body>
    <para styleclass="Heading HowTo Toggle_atoc_"><image src="tog_plus.gif" scale="100.00%" styleclass="Heading HowTo Toggle_atoc_"></image><tab/><toggle type="dropdown" print-expanded="true" help-expanded="false" defaultstyle="false" translate="true" src-collapsed="tog_plus.gif" src-expanded="tog_minus.gif" src-print="none" styleclass="Heading HowTo Toggle_atoc_"><caption translate="true"><![CDATA[HTML links to specific pages and named destinations in a PDF]]></caption><title translate="true">&lt;%EXTOGGLE%&gt;</title></toggle></para>
    <para styleclass="Body Text"><table styleclass="Default" rowcount="1" colcount="1">
      <tr style="vertical-align:top">
        <td>
          <para styleclass="Body Text"><text styleclass="Body Text" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true">Support and restrictions of HTML links to PDF:</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text"><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">You can link to specific pages and named destinations in PDFs generated by Help &amp; Manual from both H&amp;M WebHelp help documents and other HTML pages. However, links to page numbers and named destinations in PDFs do not work in CHM (HTML Help) files. This appears to be a restriction of the Microsoft CHM viewer.</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Heading Toggle_atocs_"><image src="hmtoggle_plus0.gif" scale="100.00%" styleclass="Heading Toggle_atocs_"></image><tab/><toggle type="dropdown" print-expanded="true" help-expanded="false" defaultstyle="false" translate="true" src-collapsed="hmtoggle_plus0.gif" src-expanded="hmtoggle_plus1.gif" src-print="none" styleclass="Heading Toggle_atocs_"><caption translate="true"><![CDATA[HTML links to PDF page numbers]]></caption><title translate="true">&lt;%EXTOGGLE%&gt;</title></toggle></para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo"><table styleclass="Default" rowcount="1" colcount="1">
            <tr style="vertical-align:top">
              <td>
                <para styleclass="Body Text"><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">You can create Internet links to PDF files that target a specific page in the PDF. This will work with PDFs created with Help &amp; Manual and with most other PDFs, although you should always test it first because it does not work universally.</text></para>
                <list id="20" type="ol" listtype="decimal" formatstring="%0:s." format-charset="DEFAULT_CHARSET" levelreset="true" legalstyle="false" startfrom="1" styleclass="HowTo Numbered" style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; color:#000000;">
                  <li styleclass="HowTo Numbered"><text styleclass="HowTo Numbered" translate="true">If the PDF you are linking to is created with Help &amp; Manual it must be generated using the &quot;interactive PDF&quot; option in your </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="HM_ProjectProps_PDFEx_Layout" styleclass="HowTo Numbered" translate="true">PDF settings</link><text styleclass="HowTo Numbered" translate="true">.</text><text styleclass="HowTo Numbered" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true"> </text></li>
                  <li style="margin-bottom:10px; margin-left:15px;"><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">Create an Internet link to the PDF file you want to open, using the normal URL syntax for Internet links.</text><text styleclass="Body Text" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true"> </text></li>
                  <li style="margin-bottom:10px; margin-left:15px;"><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">Add </text><text styleclass="T_Entry" translate="true">#page=x</text><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true"> directly after the PDF filename, where &quot;x&quot; is the page number you want to jump to. </text></li>
                </list>
                <para styleclass="Body Text"><text styleclass="Body Text" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true">Important note:</text><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true"> </text><br/><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">When referenced from HTML links, PDF files are numbered consecutively, starting with 1 on the first page, even if this is the cover page. </text></para>
                <para styleclass="Heading3" style="margin-left:0px;"><text styleclass="Heading3" translate="true">Examples:</text></para>
                <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo" style="margin-left:24px;"><text styleclass="T_Menu 10p" translate="true">http://www.ec-software.com/PDF/myfile.pdf#page=264</text><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true"> (absolute link to a PDF)</text></para>
                <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo" style="margin-left:24px;"><text styleclass="T_Menu 10p" translate="true">myfile.pdf#page=264 </text><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true">(relative link to a PDF in the current folder)</text></para>
                <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo" style="margin-left:24px;"><text styleclass="T_Menu 10p" translate="true">../myfile.pdf#page=264</text><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true"> (relative link to a PDF in the folder above the current folder)</text></para>
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table></para>
          <para styleclass="Heading Toggle_atocs_"><image src="hmtoggle_plus0.gif" scale="100.00%" styleclass="Heading Toggle_atocs_"></image><tab/><toggle type="dropdown" print-expanded="true" help-expanded="false" defaultstyle="false" translate="true" src-collapsed="hmtoggle_plus0.gif" src-expanded="hmtoggle_plus1.gif" src-print="none" styleclass="Heading Toggle_atocs_"><caption translate="true"><![CDATA[HTML links to named destinations in PDFs]]></caption><title translate="true">&lt;%EXTOGGLE%&gt;</title></toggle></para>
          <para style="margin-left:24px;"><table styleclass="Default" rowcount="1" colcount="1">
            <tr style="vertical-align:top">
              <td>
                <para styleclass="Body Text"><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">Help &amp; Manual automatically generates a number of named destinations in your PDF files,which can be used as link targets in the same way as </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="HM_Working_Links_Anchors" styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">anchors</link><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">. You don&apos;t need to use named destinations for normal topic links topics inside a project, those work in PDFs without any action on your part. However, named destinations are useful if you want to link to a specific location in a PDF from a HTML page, another PDF file or an application. </text></para>
                <para styleclass="Body Text"><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">See </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="HM_Working_Links_PDFdestinations" styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">Named destinations in PDF</link><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true"> for full details on the available named destinations you can use.</text></para>
                <list id="21" type="ol" listtype="decimal" formatstring="%0:s." format-charset="DEFAULT_CHARSET" levelreset="true" legalstyle="false" startfrom="1" styleclass="HowTo Numbered" style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; color:#000000;">
                  <li styleclass="HowTo Numbered"><text styleclass="HowTo Numbered" translate="true">If the PDF you are linking to is created with Help &amp; Manual it must be generated using the &quot;interactive PDF&quot; option in your </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="HM_ProjectProps_PDFEx_Layout" styleclass="HowTo Numbered" translate="true">PDF settings</link><text styleclass="HowTo Numbered" translate="true">.</text><text styleclass="HowTo Numbered" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true"> </text></li>
                  <li style="margin-bottom:10px; margin-left:15px;"><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">Create an Internet link to the PDF file you want to open, using the normal URL syntax for Internet links.</text><text styleclass="Body Text" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true"> </text></li>
                  <li style="margin-bottom:10px; margin-left:15px;"><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">Add </text><text styleclass="T_Entry" translate="true">#nameddest=destination</text><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true"> directly after the PDF filename, where &quot;destination&quot; is the the named destination you want to jump to. This is case-sensitive, upper and lower case must match the actual destination exactly.</text></li>
                </list>
                <para styleclass="Body Text"><text styleclass="Body Text" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true">Note:</text><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true"> </text><br/><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">You can also use the abbreviated syntax </text><text styleclass="T_Entry" translate="true">#destination</text><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">, which is supported by all current versions of Adobe Reader.</text></para>
                <para styleclass="Heading3" style="margin-left:0px;"><text styleclass="Heading3" translate="true">Examples:</text></para>
                <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo" style="margin-left:24px;"><text styleclass="T_Menu 10p" translate="true">http://www.ec-software.com/PDF/myfile.pdf#nameddest=TOC</text><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true"> (links to the TOC section in an H&amp;M PDF)</text></para>
                <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo" style="margin-left:24px;"><text styleclass="T_Menu 10p" translate="true">myfile.pdf#nameddest=TOPICS </text><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true">(links to the beginning of the topics section)</text></para>
                <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo" style="margin-left:24px;"><text styleclass="T_Menu 10p" translate="true">../myfile.pdf#Intro_Topic</text><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true"> (links to the topic with the ID Intro_Topic, short syntax version)</text></para>
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table></para>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </table></para>
  </body>
